<div class="bg-zinc-950 text-zinc-100">
  <.marketing_nav current_user={@current_user} current={:docs} />

  <section class="py-12 sm:py-16">
    <.docs_layout
      current="mcp-reference"
      toc={[
        {"protocol-methods", "Protocol methods"},
        {"tools", "Twelve fixed tools"},
        {"discovery", "Discovery"},
        {"running-an-action", "Running an action"},
        {"operations", "Operations and recovery"},
        {"waits", "Waits and cancellation"},
        {"runbooks-signing", "Runbooks and signing"},
        {"errors", "Errors"}
      ]}
    >
      <.docs_header current="mcp-reference">
        <:dek>
          The fixed tools, identifiers, and recovery semantics of the emisar MCP server. For client
          setup, see <.link
            navigate={~p"/docs/connect-an-llm"}
            class="font-medium text-brand-300 hover:text-brand-200"
          >Connect an LLM</.link>.
        </:dek>
      </.docs_header>

      <article class="mt-4 [&_h2]:mb-4 [&_h2]:mt-12 [&_h2]:scroll-mt-24 [&_h2]:text-xl [&_h2]:font-bold [&_h2]:text-zinc-50 [&_p]:my-4 [&_p]:leading-7 [&_p]:text-zinc-400 [&_code]:rounded [&_code]:bg-zinc-900 [&_code]:px-1.5 [&_code]:py-0.5 [&_code]:text-[0.85em] [&_code]:text-brand-300 [&_a]:font-medium [&_a]:text-brand-300 [&_a:hover]:text-brand-200 [&_ul]:my-4 [&_ul]:list-disc [&_ul]:space-y-1.5 [&_ul]:pl-5 [&_li]:text-zinc-400">
        <h2 id="protocol-methods">Protocol methods</h2>
        <p>
          emisar speaks JSON-RPC 2.0 over MCP Streamable HTTP. The current negotiated protocol is <code>2025-11-25</code>;
          <code>2025-06-18</code>
          remains supported. The endpoint is stateless: it does not issue an
          <code>Mcp-Session-Id</code>
          or require sticky routing.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><code>initialize</code> returns capabilities and operating instructions.</li>
          <li><code>ping</code> remains responsive while another request waits.</li>
          <li><code>tools/list</code> always returns the same twelve tool descriptors.</li>
          <li><code>tools/call</code> invokes one fixed tool.</li>
          <li>
            <code>notifications/cancelled</code> stops observation of one in-flight request and
            receives no response.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Request IDs are strings or integers and are returned with the same JSON type. A frame
          without an ID is a notification. Mutation notifications never execute: a mutation needs
          a request ID so its operation can be recovered safely.
        </p>

        <h2 id="tools">Twelve fixed tools</h2>
        <p>
          Actions are data, not MCP tool descriptors. Runner and pack changes appear in discovery
          results, so clients never need a hand-maintained action allowlist and never load hundreds
          of action schemas during setup.
        </p>
        <div class="my-6 overflow-x-auto rounded-xl border border-zinc-900">
          <table class="w-full min-w-[680px] text-left text-sm">
            <thead class="border-b border-zinc-900 text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-zinc-400">
              <tr>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-medium">Tool</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-medium">Purpose</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-zinc-900 text-zinc-400">
              <%= for {tool, purpose} <- [
                {"list_packs", "List in-scope packs with bounded action summaries and deployment issues."},
                {"list_runners", "Inspect runner connectivity, compatibility, and exact runner refs."},
                {"find_actions", "Find a bounded set of actions by task or exact identifiers."},
                {"get_action", "Read one immutable action contract and its compatible runners."},
                {"run_action", "Dispatch one exact action to one or more selected runners."},
                {"get_operation", "Recover one exact mutation after an ambiguous response."},
                {"wait_for_run", "Wait for one run to change or reach a terminal state."},
                {"recent_runs", "Inspect scoped run history with exact identity filters."},
                {"list_runbooks", "List visible immutable published runbooks."},
                {"get_runbook", "Read one frozen runbook and its ordered steps."},
                {"execute_runbook", "Execute one published runbook through policy and approval."},
                {"create_runbook_draft", "Save an agent-proposed draft for human review."}
              ] do %>
                <tr>
                  <td class="px-4 py-3 align-top font-mono text-xs text-brand-300">{tool}</td>
                  <td class="px-4 py-3 align-top">{purpose}</td>
                </tr>
              <% end %>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="discovery">Discovery</h2>
        <p>
          Start broad only when the task needs it. <code>list_packs</code>
          gives a bounded overview; <code>find_actions</code>
          ranks candidates; <code>get_action</code>
          returns the exact
          argument schema and current compatible runner refs. Use <code>list_runners</code>
          for fleet
          diagnosis or target selection. Pack and runner pages default to 15 items.
        </p>
        <p>
          <code>availability: "executable"</code>
          is the normal path and omits capabilities that
          cannot run anywhere in scope. <code>availability: "all"</code>
          is diagnostic: it preserves
          unavailable packs and actions together with issue codes such as disconnected,
          untrusted, retired, or descriptor mismatch.
        </p>
        <p>
          A <code>pack_ref</code>
          has the immutable form <code>pack@version/sha256:hash</code>. A <code>runner_ref</code>
          has the generation-bound form <code>name~sha256-prefix</code>. Copy both exactly from discovery; a reconnect, reinstall,
          rename, or pack change can make an earlier selection stale.
        </p>

        <h2 id="running-an-action">Running an action</h2>
        <p><code>run_action</code> accepts one explicit execution intent:</p>
        <div class="my-6 overflow-x-auto rounded-xl border border-zinc-900">
          <table class="w-full min-w-[680px] text-left text-sm">
            <thead class="border-b border-zinc-900 text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-zinc-400">
              <tr>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-medium">Field</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-medium">Requirement</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-medium">Meaning</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-zinc-900 text-zinc-400">
              <%= for {field, requirement, meaning} <- [
                {"action_id", "Required", "Exact action returned by get_action."},
                {"pack_ref", "Required", "Immutable pack generation returned by discovery."},
                {"runner_refs", "Required", "One to sixteen distinct, explicit targets."},
                {"args", "Required", "One JSON object validated against the trusted action schema."},
                {"reason", "Required", "Operator-facing audit reason for this execution."},
                {"wait", "Optional", "0 or an integer ms/s duration; default and maximum 60s."}
              ] do %>
                <tr>
                  <td class="px-4 py-3 align-top font-mono text-xs text-brand-300">{field}</td>
                  <td class="px-4 py-3 align-top whitespace-nowrap text-zinc-300">
                    {requirement}
                  </td>
                  <td class="px-4 py-3 align-top">{meaning}</td>
                </tr>
              <% end %>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p>
          Dispatch preflight re-resolves the complete target set, pack trust, descriptor, schema,
          policy, certificate window, and signature requirement. It creates the complete fan-out or
          nothing; it never silently drops a stale target. Policy can still produce a mix of allowed,
          pending-approval, and denied runs inside the accepted operation.
        </p>

        <h2 id="operations">Operations and recovery</h2>
        <p>
          Every <code>run_action</code>, <code>execute_runbook</code>, and
          <code>create_runbook_draft</code>
          receives a private <code>operation_id</code>. The stdio bridge derives it from its private
          process nonce and request sequence; for native HTTP clients, the portal derives it from
          the exact request and credential lineage. The portal reserves it in the same transaction
          as the mutation.
          Repeating the same request and facts returns the original resource; changed facts
          conflict. Models do not create operation identifiers.
        </p>
        <p>
          A successful mutation returns its operation ID. If the bridge loses an HTTP response, its
          correlated JSON-RPC error includes that same ID. After a mutation, pass it to
          <code>get_operation</code>
          before deciding whether to issue new work. Read calls retry
          normally. Run history is for investigation; it is not a substitute for exact operation
          recovery.
        </p>

        <h2 id="waits">Waits and cancellation</h2>
        <p>
          <code>run_action</code>
          waits up to 60 seconds. <code>wait_for_run</code>
          waits up to 60 seconds and returns the current state when its deadline expires. One
          credential lineage may hold eight waits per portal node. The stdio bridge also keeps up
          to eight requests in flight and uses a 90-second HTTP deadline, so pings and unrelated
          calls remain responsive. Cancelling after send stops observation only; it does not roll
          back committed infrastructure work.
        </p>

        <h2 id="runbooks-signing">Runbooks and signing</h2>
        <p>
          Published runbooks are immutable <code>slug@version</code> records. Inspect the frozen
          steps with <code>get_runbook</code> before calling <code>execute_runbook</code>. Draft
          creation only saves a reviewable draft; it never publishes or executes it.
        </p>
        <p>
          The MCP projection is limited to 32 steps, 16 resolved runners per step, 256 runs total,
          and a 56 KiB encoded definition. Larger operator-authored runbooks remain available in
          the console but are not exposed or executable through MCP. Execution returns after its
          first wave commits; follow the returned <code>wait_for_run</code>
          continuation to observe
          progress.
        </p>
        <p>
          Customer-CA signing currently protects only <code>run_action</code>. A runbook that targets
          a signature-enforcing runner fails closed with <code>signed_runbook_unsupported</code>;
          execute its steps as individually signed actions instead.
        </p>

        <h2 id="errors">Errors</h2>
        <div class="my-6 overflow-x-auto rounded-xl border border-zinc-900">
          <table class="w-full min-w-[680px] text-left text-sm">
            <thead class="border-b border-zinc-900 text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-zinc-400">
              <tr>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-medium">Code</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-medium">Meaning</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-medium">Next step</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-zinc-900 text-zinc-400">
              <%= for {code, meaning, next} <- [
                {"target_contract_changed", "The selected action, pack, or runner generation is stale.", "Call get_action again and make a fresh selection."},
                {"pack_untrusted", "The exact pack hash has not been trusted.", "A human trusts it on the Packs page."},
                {"pack_retired", "A critical update retired this exact pack.", "Update the pack or explicitly re-trust it."},
                {"pending_approval", "Policy parked the run for a human decision.", "Call wait_for_run until it changes."},
                {"operation_conflict", "One operation ID was reused with different facts.", "Treat it as a security error; do not retry."},
                {"signed_runbook_unsupported", "A runbook includes signature-enforcing targets.", "Use individually signed run_action calls."}
              ] do %>
                <tr>
                  <td class="px-4 py-3 align-top font-mono text-xs text-amber-300">{code}</td>
                  <td class="px-4 py-3 align-top">{meaning}</td>
                  <td class="px-4 py-3 align-top">{next}</td>
                </tr>
              <% end %>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p>
          Every dispatch, approval, denial, and terminal result is recorded. See
          <.link navigate={~p"/docs/audit-and-siem"}>the audit trail</.link>
          and <.link navigate={~p"/docs/policies-and-approvals"}>policies &amp; approvals</.link>.
        </p>
      </article>
    </.docs_layout>
  </section>

  <.marketing_footer />
</div>
